<DOC><DOCNO> AP890418-0062 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-18-89 0735EST</FILEID><FIRST>u i PM-Korea 1stLd-Writethru a0477 04-18 0553</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Korea, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0477,0568</SECOND><HEAD>Riot Police Break Up Strikes, Students Clash With Police</HEAD><HEAD>Eds: LEADS with six grafs to UPDATE with student-police clashes inthree cities but protests peaceful in Seoul. Picks up 5th pvs, `About 18,000...'</HEAD><BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Police firing tear gas stormed fourfactories held by strikers and arrested 175 workers today, and thegovernment warned it would use troops to keep vital industriesrunning if labor unrest spreads.   Also today, radical students battled riot police in three cities.   Officials said riot police seized the electronics and machineryfactories at dawn in Puchon on the western outskirts of Seoul afterstrikers refused to give up. Some strikers hurled firebombs androcks at the officers, but police officials said they had noreports of serious injuries.   Radical students calling for the overthrow of President RohTae-woo's government staged campus protests in Seoul and othercities today, the eve of the anniversary of a student uprising onApril 19, 1960.   Students hurling firebombs and rocks battled riot police incampus clashes in the provincial cities of Chonju, Suwon and Taejonwhen authorities blocked them from marching into the streets.Yonhap, the South Korean news agency, said about 2,500 studentswere involved in the provincial protests.   About 8,000 students shouting ``Down with dictatorship!'' and''Yankee go home!'' staged a peaceful march through eastern Seoul.Thousands of riot police watched but did not intervene apart from afew minor scuffles.   About 18,000 riot police were mobilized in Seoul to preventviolent protests, officials said.   Police stormed the Seoul office of a government lawmaker andoverpowered eight students who had attacked the office withfirebombs and then occupied it, officials said.   ``Overthrow Roh Tae-woo,'' the students yelled during the attack.   The government has warned that a growing wave of strikesthreatens South Korea's political stability and the economy.   Labor Minister Chang Yung-chul urged workers and management tosettle wage disputes peacefully.   But Prime Minister Kang Young-hoon also issued orders to usetroops and military equipment to keep vital industries running ifthreatened by strikes. Kang said radicals fomenting labor unrestwould be sternly punished.   Officials said there were no immediate plans to deploy militaryforces.   Government officials charged that militant labor unions weretrying to organize a nationwide strike to mark the May 1international labor holiday. Union leaders have denied the charge.   Industrial workers, many of whom are poorly paid and work longhours in poor conditions, are demanding major wage increases toshare in South Korea's growing prosperity.   The government ordered a major crackdown on labor disputes afterRoh warned last week that strikes threatened to hamstring theeconomy. He said walkouts had cost $2.4 billion in lost productionand that exports were down $600 million so far this year.   Two of the country's three car producers, Daewoo and Kia, saidtoday they had resumed partial production after being forced tohalt operations Monday.   But Hyundai, the nation's biggest car producer, said it had notresumed operations because of strikes and a shortage of spare parts.   Also today, some 200 journalists staged a peaceful protest inSeoul to denounce the government for arresting two journalists whowanted to visit communist North Korea. The protesters said thegovernment was trying to suppress press freedom.</TEXT></DOC>